Feed post

Yash PratapYash Pratap • YouVerified • You Web Dev, System Design, AIWeb Dev, System Design, AI 1w • 1 week ago • Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn
Chetan Bhagat became famous because of hashtag#3Idiots, and yet, on Sonam Wangchuk’s arrest, he and others said nothing.

This is the kind of success model we are selling to our society:

Be opportunistic.

It can work for upper-middle-class people who can migrate to a better country, but not for ordinary people. The day we understand this simple fact, people like Chetan Bhagat and other jokers will be debunked.

The day we realize that most influencers and celebrities have no spine at all, we will be liberated from this fake rat race and peer pressure.

hashtag#Chetan_Bhagat is the real hashtag#Chatur.

Zia Nomani • 2nd

Director - Blossom Media Pvt Ltd
6d
Do we really consider celebrities as models of success?

I think it’s time we change that perspective. To me, they’re just good entertainers and nothing more. If you’re looking for real role models, look around; our land is filled with true heroes. Some are still among us, and many have become legends long after they’re gone.

Remember, we become what we read and what we consume and in the same way, we begin to mirror the people we idolize.

Real heroes are the army personnel guarding our borders, teachers shaping young minds, businessmen who succeed with integrity, and sportsmen who make the nation proud despite limited resources (and no, not the cricketers or footballers we see on TV). They are the men who turned barren land into lush forests, or the lonely soul who carved a road through a mountain with his own hands.

These are the people worth admiring the ones who truly define success.

Except for a few who can be counted on our fingertips, the majority of celebrities are opportunistic. They speak or act only after considering it will impact their image or contribute to their bank balance.

You may differ from me and I totally respect that.
